    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0f50a27d-5b84-4848-899c-a6f4ada7a9a9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 4-year-old girl who appears tired, clingy, and less playful than usual. She is brought in by her mother after 4 days of fever with chills, worsening cough, and reduced appetite. Her cheeks are flushed, and she intermittently curls up against her mother between coughing spells. She looks mildly dehydrated with dry lips and has noticeably faster breathing than expected for her age. During the examination she is alert but irritable, preferring to sit upright in her mother’s lap.\n\nOver the past two days, {patientName} has developed shortness of breath with activity and occasional chest discomfort when coughing. Her mother reports poor sleep because of nighttime cough, nasal congestion, and noisy breathing with intermittent snoring when she lies flat during this illness. She has had less interest in food and fluids, though she still takes small sips of water and juice. There has been no vomiting. She has complained of a mild headache and has been more fatigued and has wanted to nap more often than usual. After several forceful coughing fits, her mother noticed a very small streak of blood in the mucus once, without ongoing bleeding. Her mother has also noticed mild belly discomfort during coughing spells, which is common in young children with lower respiratory infections.\n\nAt baseline, {patientName} is an active preschooler who attends daycare, enjoys drawing, building blocks, and playing outdoors with neighborhood children. She also likes pretend play in the family basement playroom, which can be dusty, and helps feed the family’s pet cat. She lives with her parents and an older brother in a smoke-free home, but her maternal grandmother who babysits some afternoons smokes outside and occasionally smells of cigarette smoke when she comes in. Several children at daycare recently had colds, and daycare attendance gives her frequent viral exposures. As a preschool child she does not have independent disease-causing habits such as smoking, but her routine behaviors and environment can still increase risk: frequent close-contact play at daycare, inconsistent hand-to-face hygiene typical for her age, and regular play in dusty spaces that can aggravate her airways during viral illnesses.\n\nShe is small but well nourished for age, weighing 16.4 kg, with clothing and hygiene appropriate to the season. She is fully ambulatory and developmentally appropriate, speaking in short sentences and interacting with familiar caregivers. She has a history of mild intermittent wheezing with viral infections, and today her presentation is consistent with an acute lower respiratory infection causing fever, cough, tachypnea, focal crackles, and mild respiratory distress. There are no signs suggesting lung abscess, no features of pneumonitis, and no signs of neglect or trauma. She has no loss of smell by history and no psychiatric symptoms; congenital anosmia and factitious psychosis are unrelated conditions and are not present."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
